{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013GEpKSpEYLCY2uE2df4vQB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture. The precondition `transform_scenario_fixture` ran its probe (checking if the transform already exists), and since the transform did NOT exist (404), it ran the apply steps. The apply steps:\n\n1. Ensured the es-transform StatefulSet exists\n2. Scaled it up to 1 replica\n3. Waited for it ready\n4. Seeded source docs into `app-events` index\n5. Created and started the transform `events-by-service`\n6. Polled until checkpoint >= 1 (captured baseline)\n7. THEN SCALED `es-transform` BACK TO 0 (re-injected the fault)\n8. Added new docs to the source to generate more data\n\nThe fixture set up a transform on `app-events` that rolls up to `app-events-rollup`, captured the checkpoint baseline in a ConfigMap, then deliberately scaled down the transform node to simulate a failure. Now my role is to verify the elastic-password secret hasn't been corrupted, restore the transform capacity by scaling es-transform back up, and ensure the node has the proper `transform` role to actually run transforms.\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing myself on the role requirement. The transform did run successfully during the precondition setup even though the es-transform node only had the `ingest` role. Looking at ES 7.17 behavior, if no node explicitly has the `transform` role assigned, transforms still execute on any available node—they don't fail outright. Let me verify what actually happened in the precondition phase. exist have been created. So why does the transform return 404 now? Either the apply failed silently, or something deleted the transform after it was created. Given that the `es-transform` StatefulSet was scaled to 0, maybe the transform gets cleaned up when its node disappears, or maybe the fixture's apply step never actually succeeded in creating it. I'm realizing the semantic